                    <div class="accordion-header collapsed" data-target="c1" onclick="toggleAccordion(event, 'c1')">
                      ORIGINS OF A RESTLESS GENIUS
                      <span class="chev">â–¶</span>
                    </div>
                    <div id="c1" class="accordion-body">
                      <p>Rahul Dev Burmanâ€”universally known as Panchamâ€”was born into a musical dynasty that shaped the very evolution of Indian cinema. His father, the iconic S. D. Burman, carried within him the weight of classical tradition, the wisdom of folk roots, and an instinctive melodic purity that had already reshaped Hindi film music.</p>
                      <p>Yet, even as a child, Pancham showed signs of a different temperamentâ€”one driven not by inherited legacy but by an almost electric sense of curiosity. Where S. D. Burman glided like a river of timeless melody, Pancham moved like a spark that refused to stay still.</p>
                      <p>He was restless.<br>He was rhythmic.<br>He was experimental.<br>He was hungry.</p>
                      <p>Stories from his childhood describe him tapping rhythms on tabletops, tin boxes, drawers, metal railingsâ€”anything that could produce a sound. His ear sensed beats where others heard silence. His fingers found percussion where others found stillness.</p>

                      <h4>When the Son Became the Composer</h4>
                      <p>The turning point came when S. D. Burman fell critically ill during the production of two landmark films: Guide (1965) and Aradhana (1969). In those crucial days, a young and uncredited Pancham stepped forward.</p>
                      <p>Two songsâ€”both destined to become immortalâ€”were quietly composed by him:</p>
                      <p>â€œGaata Rahe Mera Dilâ€ (Guide)<br>â€œKora Kagaz Tha Yeh Mann Meraâ€ (Aradhana)</p>
                      <p>Both songs matched S. D. Burmanâ€™s standards, yet had a subtle undercurrent of newness, a youthful buoyancy that was undeniably Pancham. These were early signs that a revolution was on the horizon.</p>

                      <h4>A Unique Musical Mind</h4>
                      <p>People who worked with him described Panchamâ€™s creative energy as â€œa storm in slow motionâ€â€”constantly thinking, inventing, hearing something new inside his head.</p>
                      <p>To many, he seemed mischievous, playful, spontaneous. To musicians, he was a visionary.</p>
                      <p>To his close circle, he was a man who never stopped listening.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>

