                  <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header collapsed" data-target="c2" onclick="toggleAccordion(event, 'c2')">
                      THE MAKING OF A MUSICAL LANGUAGE
                      <span class="chev">â–¶</span>
                    </div>
                    <div id="c2" class="accordion-body">
                      <p>By the late 1960s, Pancham was constructing his own musical vocabularyâ€”something Bollywood had never experienced.</p>

                      <h4>1. Polyphony</h4>
                      <p>He introduced layered melodic movementâ€”countermelodies and intertwined linesâ€”borrowed from Western orchestration but fused with Indian emotion.</p>

                      <h4>2. Rhythmic Identity</h4>
                      <p>For Pancham, rhythm was character. Tabla tarang, madol, African percussion, Latin bongosâ€”everything blended under his command.</p>

                      <h4>3. Harmonic Modernity</h4>
                      <p>He played with unexpected chord substitutions, suspended harmonies, jazz extensions, modal shiftsâ€”giving Hindi music new emotional densities.</p>

                      <h4>4. Texture as Storytelling</h4>
                      <p>Tape-speed effects, flangers, reverb chambers, synthsâ€”RD used sound as atmosphere, not ornament.</p>

                      <p>The Pancham Sound was bornâ€”a language neither Indian nor Western but uniquely his own.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <!-- CHAPTER 3 -->
                  <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header collapsed" data-target="c3" onclick="toggleAccordion(event, 'c3')">
                      EXPERIMENTS THAT CHANGED INDIAN MUSIC
                      <span class="chev">â–¶</span>
                    </div>
                    <div id="c3" class="accordion-body">
                      <p>For R. D. Burman, experimentation was not an event â€” it was a lifestyle. He approached sound with the mind of a scientist, the heart of a poet, and the curiosity of a child. Any object could become an instrument, any sonic accident could become a masterpiece, and any unexpected sound could become history.</p>

                      <h4>The â€œMillion-Dollar Mistakeâ€ â€” Chingari Koi Bhadke</h4>
                      <p>During the recording of â€œChingari Koi Bhadkeâ€ from Amar Prem, guitarist Bhanu Gupta accidentally struck a wrong chord. Instead of stopping, Pancham asked him to repeat it. That accidental tension became the emotional spine of the entire prelude â€” now famously known as the â€œMillion-Dollar Mistake.â€</p>

                      <h4>Distorted vocal effect â€” â€œDuniya Mein Logon Koâ€</h4>
                      <p>Long before digital processors existed, RD created a psychedelic vocal wobble through tape-speed manipulation, layered doubling, and EQ shaping. This became Bollywoodâ€™s first iconic vocal distortion.</p>

                      <h4>Flanger effect â€” â€œDhanno Ki Aankhon Meinâ€</h4>
                      <p>RD introduced the analog flanger to Indian cinema, creating the swirling, liquid texture that defined the songâ€™s mood.</p>

                      <h4>Gargled sound â€” â€œSatte Pe Sattaâ€</h4>
                      <p>RD asked Annette Pinto to gargle water in rhythm to create the filmâ€™s comic sound signature â€” a daring experiment that became a cult favorite.</p>

                      <h4>Beer bottle tones â€” â€œMehbooba Mehboobaâ€</h4>
                      <p>On a rainy evening, RD and his team blew across the mouths of half-filled beer bottles. Fifteen days later, that sound became part of the legendary â€œMehboobaâ€ rhythm structure.</p>

                      <h4>Guitar as â€œrhythmic dhaâ€</h4>
                      <p>RD turned a single repeated guitar chord into the rhythmic heartbeat of many songs â€” a kind of â€œdhaâ€ that anchored his grooves.</p>

                      <h4>Madol revolution â€” Ranjit Gazmer</h4>
                      <p>With Nepali arranger Ranjit Gazmer, RD introduced the madol into mainstream Bollywood rhythms â€” an earthy pulse that shaped many of his energetic tracks.</p>

                      <h4>Minimalist masterpiece â€” â€œMusafir Hoon Yaaronâ€</h4>
                      <p>RD crafted a wandering, introspective mood using sparse guitar, harmonica lines, and Kishore Kumarâ€™s intimate voice. It was cinematic minimalism at its best.</p>
                    </div>
